#: src/overrides.md:1
msgid "Overrides"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:3
msgid ""
"`rustup` automatically determines which [toolchain](concepts/toolchains.md) "
"to use when one of the installed commands like `rustc` is executed. There "
"are several ways to control and override which toolchain is used:"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:7
msgid ""
"A [toolchain override shorthand](#toolchain-override-shorthand) used on the "
"command-line, such as `cargo +beta`."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:9
msgid "The `RUSTUP_TOOLCHAIN` environment variable."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:10
msgid ""
"A [directory override](#directory-overrides), set with the `rustup override` "
"command."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:11
msgid "The [`rust-toolchain.toml`](#the-toolchain-file) file."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:12
msgid "The [default toolchain](#default-toolchain)."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:14
msgid ""
"The toolchain is chosen in the order listed above, using the first one that "
"is specified. There is one exception though: directory overrides and the "
"`rust-toolchain.toml` file are also preferred by their proximity to the "
"current directory. That is, these two override methods are discovered by "
"walking up the directory tree toward the filesystem root, and a `rust-"
"toolchain.toml` file that is closer to the current directory will be "
"preferred over a directory override that is further away."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:22
msgid "To verify which toolchain is active, you can use `rustup show`."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:30
msgid "Toolchain override shorthand"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:32
msgid ""
"The `rustup` toolchain proxies can be instructed directly to use a specific "
"toolchain, a convenience for developers who often test different toolchains. "
"If the first argument to `cargo`, `rustc` or other tools in the toolchain "
"begins with `+`, it will be interpreted as a `rustup` toolchain name, and "
"that toolchain will be preferred, as in"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:42
msgid "Directory overrides"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:44
msgid ""
"Directories can be assigned their own Rust toolchain with `rustup override`. "
"When a directory has an override then any time `rustc` or `cargo` is run "
"inside that directory, or one of its child directories, the override "
"toolchain will be invoked."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:49
msgid "To use to a specific nightly for a directory:"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:55
msgid "Or a specific stable release:"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:61
msgid ""
"To see the active toolchain use `rustup show`. To remove the override and "
"use the default toolchain again, `rustup override unset`."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:64
msgid ""
"The per-directory overrides are stored in [a configuration file]"
"(configuration.md) in `rustup`'s home directory."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:69
msgid "The toolchain file"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:71
msgid ""
"Some projects find themselves 'pinned' to a specific release of Rust and "
"want this information reflected in their source repository. This is most "
"often the case for nightly-only software that pins to a revision from the "
"release archives."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:76
msgid ""
"In these cases the toolchain can be named in the project's directory in a "
"file called `rust-toolchain.toml` or `rust-toolchain`. If both files are "
"present in a directory, the latter is used for backwards compatibility. The "
"files use the [TOML](https://toml.io/) format and have the following layout:"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:83
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[toolchain]\n"
"channel = \"nightly-2020-07-10\"\n"
"components = [ \"rustfmt\", \"rustc-dev\" ]\n"
"targets = [ \"wasm32-unknown-unknown\", \"thumbv2-none-eabi\" ]\n"
"profile = \"minimal\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:91
msgid ""
"The `[toolchain]` section is mandatory, and at least one property must be "
"specified. `channel` and `path` are mutually exclusive."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:94
msgid ""
"For backwards compatibility, `rust-toolchain` files also support a legacy "
"format that only contains a toolchain name without any TOML encoding, e.g. "
"just `nightly-2021-01-21`. The file has to be encoded in US-ASCII in this "
"case (if you are on Windows, check the encoding and that it does not start "
"with a BOM). The legacy format is not available in `rust-toolchain.toml` "
"files."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:100
msgid ""
"If you see the following error (when running `rustc`, `cargo` or other "
"command)"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:106
msgid ""
"it means you're running `rustup` pre-1.23.0 and trying to interact with a "
"project that uses the new TOML encoding in the `rust-toolchain` file. You "
"need to upgrade `rustup` to 1.23.0+."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:110
msgid ""
"The `rust-toolchain.toml`/`rust-toolchain` files are suitable to check in to "
"source control. If that's done, `Cargo.lock` should probably be tracked too "
"if the toolchain is pinned to a specific release, to avoid potential "
"compatibility issues with dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:115
msgid "Toolchain file settings"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:117
msgid "channel"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:119
msgid ""
"The `channel` setting specifies which [toolchain](concepts/toolchains.md) to "
"use. The value is a string in the following form:"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:133
msgid "path"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:135
msgid ""
"The `path` setting allows a custom toolchain to be used. The value is an "
"absolute path string."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:138
msgid ""
"Since a `path` directive directly names a local toolchain, other options "
"like `components`, `targets`, and `profile` have no effect."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:141
msgid ""
"`channel` and `path` are mutually exclusive, since a `path` already points "
"to a specific toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:144
msgid "profile"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:146
msgid ""
"The `profile` setting names a group of components to be installed. The value "
"is a string. The valid options are: `minimal`, `default`, and `complete`. "
"See [profiles](concepts/profiles.md) for details of each."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:150
msgid ""
"Note that if not specified, the `default` profile is not necessarily used, "
"as a different default profile might have been set with `rustup set profile`."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:156
msgid "components"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:158
msgid ""
"The `components` setting contains a list of additional components to "
"install. The value is a list of strings. See [components](concepts/"
"components.md) for a list of components. Note that different toolchains may "
"have different components available."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:163
msgid "The components listed here are additive with the current profile."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:167
msgid "targets"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:169
msgid ""
"The `targets` setting contains a list of platforms to install for [cross-"
"compilation](https://rust-lang.github.io/rustup/cross-compilation.html). The "
"value is a list of strings."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:172
msgid ""
"The host platform is automatically included; the targets listed here are "
"additive."
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:177
msgid "Default toolchain"
msgstr ""

#: src/overrides.md:179
msgid ""
"If no other overrides are set, the global default toolchain will be used. "
"This default can be chosen when `rustup` is [installed](installation/index."
"md). The `rustup default` command can be used to set and query the current "
"default. Run `rustup default` without any arguments to print the current "
"default. Specify a toolchain as an argument to change the default:"
msgstr ""
